      <h1>How Many Tablespoons in a Cup? (Cooking Measurement Chart)</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">The quick answer: there are <strong>16 tablespoons in 1 US cup</strong>. This is one of the most frequently needed conversions in cooking and baking — especially when you are halving a recipe, missing a measuring cup, or working with small-batch quantities where precision matters. But there is much more to tablespoon-to-cup conversions than the single number. This guide covers every fraction conversion (like the tricky 1/3 cup = 5 tablespoons + 1 teaspoon), builds a complete measurement chart from cups down to teaspoons, explains international tablespoon differences that can wreck a recipe, and shares professional tips for measuring accuracy that will make your baking more consistent.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>The Basic Conversion: 16 Tablespoons = 1 Cup</h2>
    <p>In the US customary measurement system, 1 cup equals exactly 16 tablespoons. This relationship is fixed by definition — it is not an approximation or a rounding. The full conversion chain works like this: 1 cup = 8 fluid ounces, and 1 fluid ounce = 2 tablespoons, so 8 x 2 = 16 tablespoons per cup.</p>
    <p>Going smaller, 1 tablespoon = 3 teaspoons, which means 1 cup = 48 teaspoons. And going larger, 2 cups = 1 pint = 32 tablespoons, and 4 cups = 1 quart = 64 tablespoons. Once you know that 16 tablespoons equals 1 cup, every other conversion in the chain follows by simple multiplication or division.</p>
    <p>This conversion is especially useful when you are baking and need to measure a fraction of a cup but only have tablespoon measures available — a common situation when baking in small quantities, camping, or working in a minimally equipped kitchen.</p>

    <h2>Cup Fractions to Tablespoons: Complete Conversion Chart</h2>
    <p>This is the table most people are looking for — every common cup fraction converted to tablespoons and teaspoons. Some fractions (like 1/3 cup) do not convert to a whole number of tablespoons, so the chart includes the teaspoon remainder for exact measurement.</p>
    <div class="table-responsive">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Cup Amount</th><th>Tablespoons</th><th>Teaspoons</th><th>Fluid Ounces</th><th>Milliliters</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1 cup</td><td>16</td><td>48</td><td>8</td><td>237</td></tr>
          <tr><td>3/4 cup</td><td>12</td><td>36</td><td>6</td><td>177</td></tr>
          <tr><td>2/3 cup</td><td>10 + 2 tsp</td><td>32</td><td>5.3</td><td>158</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/2 cup</td><td>8</td><td>24</td><td>4</td><td>118</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/3 cup</td><td>5 + 1 tsp</td><td>16</td><td>2.7</td><td>79</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/4 cup</td><td>4</td><td>12</td><td>2</td><td>59</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/8 cup</td><td>2</td><td>6</td><td>1</td><td>30</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/16 cup</td><td>1</td><td>3</td><td>0.5</td><td>15</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The two trickiest conversions deserve extra attention. <strong>1/3 cup</strong> = 5 tablespoons + 1 teaspoon (not 5.33 tablespoons — you cannot easily measure a third of a tablespoon, but 1 teaspoon is exactly one-third of a tablespoon). <strong>2/3 cup</strong> = 10 tablespoons + 2 teaspoons. These come up frequently in recipes and are worth memorizing.</p>

    <h2>Complete Measurement Hierarchy: Cup to Pinch</h2>
    <p>For complete kitchen reference, here is every standard US measurement unit from cups down to the smallest informal measures. This table bridges the gap between the relatively large cup measurements and the tiny amounts used for spices, extracts, and leavening agents.</p>
    <div class="table-responsive">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Unit</th><th>Equivalent</th><th>Milliliters</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>1 cup</td><td>16 tablespoons / 48 teaspoons</td><td>236.6</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1 fluid ounce</td><td>2 tablespoons / 6 teaspoons</td><td>29.6</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1 tablespoon (tbsp)</td><td>3 teaspoons</td><td>14.8</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1 teaspoon (tsp)</td><td>1/3 tablespoon</td><td>4.9</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/2 teaspoon</td><td>1/6 tablespoon</td><td>2.5</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/4 teaspoon</td><td>1/12 tablespoon</td><td>1.2</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/8 teaspoon</td><td>1 "pinch"</td><td>0.6</td></tr>
          <tr><td>1/16 teaspoon</td><td>1 "dash"</td><td>0.3</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The terms "pinch" and "dash" have no official definition, but in culinary convention, a pinch is generally accepted as approximately 1/8 teaspoon (what you can pick up between your thumb and forefinger) and a dash is about 1/16 teaspoon. For baking, where precision matters, avoid these imprecise terms and use exact teaspoon fractions instead.</p>

    <h2>Doubling and Halving Recipes: Tablespoon Math</h2>
    <p>One of the most practical applications of the tablespoon-to-cup conversion is scaling recipes up or down. When you halve a recipe that calls for 1/3 cup, you need half of 5 tablespoons + 1 teaspoon, which is 2 tablespoons + 2 teaspoons. Here is a reference table for the most common scaling scenarios.</p>
